answer.detail:
Angular has three kinds of directives:

1. **Components** — directives with a template (the most common kind).
2. **Structural Directives** — change the DOM tree by adding, removing, or replacing elements. The `*` prefix is syntactic sugar that wraps the host element in an `<ng-template>`. For example, `*ngIf="show"` expands to `<ng-template [ngIf]="show"><div>...</div></ng-template>`.
3. **Attribute Directives** — change the look or behaviour of an element, component, or another directive without touching the DOM structure. `ngClass`, `ngStyle`, and Angular Material's `matInput` are examples.

**Angular 17+ control flow (preferred over structural directives):**
```html
@if (user) {
  <app-profile [user]="user" />
} @else {
  <p>Loading...</p>
}

@for (item of items; track item.id) {
  <li>{{ item.name }}</li>
}
```
The new syntax is compiled to efficient code and avoids the `<ng-template>` boilerplate.

**Custom attribute directive example:**
```ts
@Directive({ selector: '[appHighlight]', standalone: true })
export class HighlightDirective {
  @HostListener('mouseenter') onEnter() { ... }
}
```

