**NgModule-based (legacy) approach:**
Components must be declared in exactly one NgModule. NgModules control what a component can see (imports) and what it exports to others.

```ts
@NgModule({
  declarations: [UserCardComponent],
  imports: [CommonModule],
  exports: [UserCardComponent]
})
export class UserModule {}
```

**Standalone approach (Angular 17+, default):**
No NgModule needed. The component manages its own dependencies:

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-user-card',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [CommonModule, RouterLink, DatePipe],
  template: `...`
})
export class UserCardComponent {}
```

**Migration:** `ng generate @angular/core:standalone` automates the migration from NgModule to standalone.

**When NgModules still matter:**
- Third-party libraries that haven't migrated yet
- SharedModules that bundle many directives/pipes (though standalone is generally better)
- Gradual migration: you can mix both in one app

