answer.detail:
This pattern (popularised in React by Dan Abramov, equally applicable in Angular) divides components by responsibility:

**Smart component example:**
```ts
@Component({
  template: `<app-user-list [users]="users$ | async" (select)="onSelect($event)" />`
})
export class UserPageComponent {
  users$ = inject(UserService).getUsers();
  onSelect(user: User) { inject(Router).navigate(['/user', user.id]); }
}
```

**Dumb component example:**
```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-user-list',
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  template: `@for (u of users; track u.id) { <li (click)="select.emit(u)">{{ u.name }}</li> }`
})
export class UserListComponent {
  @Input() users: User[] = [];
  @Output() select = new EventEmitter<User>();
}
```

The dumb component knows nothing about services, routing, or global state — making it a pure view function of its inputs. This makes it trivial to test and reuse across different contexts.

**ViewChild** accesses elements within the component's own template:

```ts
@Component({ template: `<canvas #myCanvas></canvas>` })
export class ChartComponent implements AfterViewInit {
  @ViewChild('myCanvas') canvasRef!: ElementRef<HTMLCanvasElement>;

  ngAfterViewInit() {
    const ctx = this.canvasRef.nativeElement.getContext('2d');
    // safe to use canvas here
  }
}
```

**ContentChild** accesses content projected by the parent into `<ng-content>`:

```ts
@Component({ template: `<ng-content></ng-content>` })
export class PanelComponent implements AfterContentInit {
  @ContentChild(HeaderComponent) header!: HeaderComponent;

  ngAfterContentInit() {
    // header is now available
  }
}
// Usage: <app-panel><app-header /></app-panel>
```

**`{ static: true }` vs `{ static: false }` (default):**
- `static: true` — resolved before change detection; element must always be in DOM (not conditional)
- `static: false` — resolved after change detection; works with conditional elements

With signals, `viewChild()` and `contentChild()` signal-based equivalents (Angular 17.1+) provide reactive access without lifecycle hook coupling.

code.snippet:
// Signal-based alternative (Angular 17.1+)
import { viewChild, contentChild } from '@angular/core';

export class MyComponent {
  canvas = viewChild<ElementRef>('myCanvas');
  // canvas() returns ElementRef | undefined — reactive, no lifecycle hook needed
}

