answer.detail:
**Creating Observables:**
```ts
const count$ = interval(1000).pipe(
  take(10),
  map(n => n * 2)
);

const click$ = fromEvent(document, 'click');
```

**Transforming with operators:**
```ts
searchResults$ = this.searchControl.valueChanges.pipe(
  debounceTime(300),           // wait 300ms after last keystroke
  distinctUntilChanged(),      // ignore if same as last value
  filter(q => q.length > 2),   // minimum 3 chars
  switchMap(q => this.api.search(q)), // cancel previous request
  catchError(err => of([]))    // handle errors gracefully
);
```

**Subscribing:**
```ts
ngOnInit() {
  this.sub = this.searchResults$.subscribe({
    next: results => this.results = results,
    error: err => console.error(err),
    complete: () => console.log('Done')
  });
}
ngOnDestroy() { this.sub.unsubscribe(); }
```

**Prefer `async` pipe** to avoid manual subscription management:
```html
<ul>
  <li *ngFor="let r of searchResults$ | async">{{ r.name }}</li>
</ul>
```

**Pattern 1 — async pipe (best for templates):**
```html
<div>{{ data$ | async }}</div>
```
Angular manages subscribe/unsubscribe automatically.

**Pattern 2 — takeUntilDestroyed (Angular 16+, best for imperative code):**
```ts
export class MyComponent {
  private destroyRef = inject(DestroyRef);

  ngOnInit() {
    this.dataService.stream$
      .pipe(takeUntilDestroyed(this.destroyRef))
      .subscribe(data => this.data = data);
  }
}
// Or inject in field initializer (outside ngOnInit):
class MyComponent {
  data$ = toSignal(this.dataService.stream$); // auto-managed
}
```

**Pattern 3 — classic destroy$ Subject:**
```ts
private destroy$ = new Subject<void>();

ngOnInit() {
  this.data$.pipe(takeUntil(this.destroy$)).subscribe(...);
}
ngOnDestroy() {
  this.destroy$.next();
  this.destroy$.complete();
}
```

**What NOT to do:**
```ts
ngOnInit() {
  // BUG: no unsubscribe — leaks if component is destroyed and recreated
  this.interval$.subscribe(val => this.count = val);
}
```

```ts
// Subject — no replay
const s = new Subject<number>();
s.subscribe(v => console.log('A:', v));
s.next(1); // A: 1
const b = s.subscribe(v => console.log('B:', v));
s.next(2); // A: 2, B: 2 — B missed the 1

// BehaviorSubject — current value on subscribe
const bs = new BehaviorSubject<number>(0); // initial: 0
bs.subscribe(v => console.log('A:', v)); // A: 0 immediately
bs.next(1); // A: 1
bs.subscribe(v => console.log('B:', v)); // B: 1 immediately (gets current)

// ReplaySubject — last N values
const rs = new ReplaySubject<number>(2); // buffer 2
rs.next(1); rs.next(2); rs.next(3);
rs.subscribe(v => console.log(v)); // 2, 3 (last 2)
```

**BehaviorSubject as state store:**
```ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CartService {
  private items$ = new BehaviorSubject<CartItem[]>([]);
  readonly cart$ = this.items$.asObservable(); // expose as read-only Observable

  addItem(item: CartItem) {
    this.items$.next([...this.items$.value, item]);
  }
}
```
Note: `asObservable()` prevents consumers from calling `.next()` directly.

**Cold Observable — each subscribe triggers a new execution:**
```ts
const http$ = this.http.get('/api/data');
// Two subscriptions = two HTTP requests!
http$.subscribe(d => console.log('A:', d));
http$.subscribe(d => console.log('B:', d));
```

**Make it hot with shareReplay:**
```ts
const shared$ = this.http.get('/api/data').pipe(
  shareReplay(1) // one HTTP call, cached for late subscribers
);
shared$.subscribe(d => console.log('A:', d)); // triggers request
shared$.subscribe(d => console.log('B:', d)); // gets cached value
```

**Hot Observable — shared producer:**
```ts
const clicks$ = fromEvent(document, 'click'); // DOM event — always hot
clicks$.subscribe(e => console.log('Handler 1'));
clicks$.subscribe(e => console.log('Handler 2')); // same click event shared
```

**In Angular:**
- `HttpClient` returns cold — each `subscribe()` fires a new request
- `Router.events` is hot — all subscribers see the same navigation events
- Use `shareReplay(1)` to cache HTTP responses used by multiple components

**Signals basics:**
```ts
export class CounterComponent {
  count = signal(0);
  doubled = computed(() => this.count() * 2); // auto-updates

  increment() { this.count.update(n => n + 1); }
}
```

**Template — reads signal by calling it:**
```html
<p>Count: {{ count() }}, Doubled: {{ doubled() }}</p>
<button (click)="increment()">+1</button>
```

**effect() for side effects:**
```ts
constructor() {
  effect(() => {
    console.log('Count changed to', this.count());
    // Runs whenever count() changes
  });
}
```

**Bridging with RxJS:**
```ts
results = toSignal(
  this.searchQuery$.pipe(switchMap(q => this.api.search(q))),
  { initialValue: [] }
);
```

**Signals vs RxJS — when to use which:**
| | Signals | RxJS |
|---|---|---|
| Sync state | Excellent | Verbose |
| Async streams | No native async | Excellent |
| Time operators | No | Yes |
| Learning curve | Low | High |
| Zoneless CD | Yes | Requires adaptation |

Best practice: use **signals for state**, **RxJS for async flows**, bridge with `toSignal`/`toObservable`.

**How Zone.js works:**
Zone.js monkey-patches `setTimeout`, `Promise`, `XMLHttpRequest`, `addEventListener`, etc. When any of these complete, Zone.js tells Angular to run change detection. Angular then walks the component tree.

**Default vs OnPush:**
```ts
// Default: checked on every CD cycle regardless
@Component({ selector: 'app-default', template: `{{ data }}` })
export class DefaultComponent {
  data = computeExpensiveValue();
}

// OnPush: only checked when inputs change or markForCheck() called
@Component({
  selector: 'app-fast',
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  template: `{{ data() }}`
})
export class FastComponent {
  @Input() data!: string; // must pass new reference, not mutate
}
```

**OnPush rules:**
- Works best with **immutable data** — mutating an array won't trigger CD; replacing it will
- Use the `async` pipe — it calls `markForCheck()` when the Observable emits
- Use signals — they bypass Zone.js entirely for fine-grained updates

**Zoneless Angular (v18+ experimental):**
```ts
bootstrapApplication(AppComponent, {
  providers: [provideExperimentalZonelessChangeDetection()]
});
```
With zoneless + signals, Angular only updates the specific DOM nodes whose signal dependencies changed — no tree traversal needed.

