**Modern functional guard (v15.2+):**
```ts
// auth.guard.ts
export const authGuard: CanActivateFn = (route, state) => {
  const auth = inject(AuthService);
  const router = inject(Router);

  return auth.isLoggedIn()
    ? true
    : router.createUrlTree(['/login'], { queryParams: { returnUrl: state.url } });
};
```

**CanDeactivate:**
```ts
export const unsavedChangesGuard: CanDeactivateFn<EditComponent> = (component) => {
  if (component.isDirty()) {
    return confirm('You have unsaved changes. Leave anyway?');
  }
  return true;
};
```

**Resolve — pre-fetch data:**
```ts
export const userResolver: ResolveFn<User> = (route) => {
  return inject(UserService).getUser(route.paramMap.get('id')!);
};

// In routes:
{ path: 'user/:id', component: UserDetailComponent, resolve: { user: userResolver } }

// In component:
ngOnInit() {
  this.user = this.route.snapshot.data['user'];
}
```

**Route configuration:**
```ts
{ path: 'admin', component: AdminComponent, canActivate: [authGuard, roleGuard] }
```

Multiple guards run sequentially; if any returns false/UrlTree, navigation is cancelled.

code.snippet:
// Functional role guard
export const roleGuard = (requiredRole: string): CanActivateFn => {
  return () => {
    const auth = inject(AuthService);
    return auth.hasRole(requiredRole) || inject(Router).createUrlTree(['/forbidden']);
  };
};

// Usage in routes:
{ path: 'admin', canActivate: [roleGuard('ADMIN')], ... }

answer.detail:
```
Source:    --A----B----C---->

switchMap:    --a1--a2-(cancel A when B arrives)
                      --b1--b2-(cancel B when C arrives)
                                --c1--c2-->

concatMap:    --a1--a2--|--b1--b2--|--c1--c2-->  (sequential)

mergeMap:     --a1--a2--b1--a3--b2--c1-->  (all concurrent)

exhaustMap:   --a1--a2--|  (B and C ignored while A is active)
```

**Use-case table:**
| Operator | Use case |
|---|---|
| `switchMap` | Type-ahead search, live route data, cancel stale requests |
| `concatMap` | Ordered save operations, sequential animations |
| `mergeMap` | Fire-and-forget parallel requests (e.g., analytics events) |
| `exhaustMap` | Login/submit buttons (prevent double-click), refresh on demand |

**Code examples:**
```ts
// switchMap — search
this.searchControl.valueChanges.pipe(
  debounceTime(300),
  switchMap(query => this.api.search(query))
).subscribe(results => ...);

// exhaustMap — login button
this.loginClick$.pipe(
  exhaustMap(creds => this.auth.login(creds))
).subscribe(...);

// concatMap — upload queue
from(fileQueue).pipe(
  concatMap(file => this.upload(file))
).subscribe(...);
```

**Reactive graph — how tracking works:**

When a `computed` or `effect` runs, Angular sets a global 'current consumer' context. Every `signal()` call reads within that context automatically registers the consumer as a dependent. When the signal's value changes via `.set()` or `.update()`, it marks all dependents as stale and schedules re-evaluation.

```ts
const a = signal(1);
const b = signal(2);
const sum = computed(() => a() + b()); // tracks a and b

console.log(sum()); // 3 — computed evaluates lazily on first read
a.set(10);
console.log(sum()); // 12 — re-computed because a changed
```

**effect() lifecycle:**
```ts
export class AppComponent {
  theme = signal<'light' | 'dark'>('light');

  constructor() {
    effect(() => {
      document.body.className = this.theme(); // runs on each theme change
    });
    // Effect is destroyed when the component is destroyed
  }
}
```

**Mutability control:**
- `signal()` — writable
- `signal.asReadonly()` — expose read-only version (like BehaviorSubject's asObservable)
- `computed()` — always read-only

**Angular 18+ resource() API for async:**
```ts
userResource = resource({
  request: () => ({ id: this.userId() }),
  loader: ({ request }) => fetch(`/api/users/${request.id}`).then(r => r.json())
});
// userResource.value() — the loaded data signal
// userResource.isLoading() — loading state signal
```

