**Basic @defer example:**
```html
@defer (on viewport) {
  <app-heavy-chart [data]="chartData" />
} @placeholder {
  <div class="chart-skeleton" style="height: 300px"></div>
} @loading (minimum 500ms) {
  <app-spinner />
} @error {
  <p>Failed to load chart. <button (click)="retry()">Retry</button></p>
}
```

**All trigger options:**
```html
@defer (on idle)            { ... }  <!-- when browser is idle -->
@defer (on viewport)        { ... }  <!-- when enters viewport (IntersectionObserver) -->
@defer (on interaction)     { ... }  <!-- on click or keydown -->
@defer (on hover)           { ... }  <!-- on mouseover -->
@defer (on timer(2000ms))   { ... }  <!-- after 2 seconds -->
@defer (when isLoggedIn())  { ... }  <!-- when condition is truthy -->
@defer (prefetch on idle)   { ... }  <!-- prefetch chunk on idle, show on another trigger -->
```

**Why it matters:**
- Reduces initial JS parse/execute time (improves LCP, TTI)
- No manual `loadComponent` in router needed for below-the-fold content
- Works at template level — not just at route level like lazy routes
- Angular CLI handles code splitting automatically — no webpack config needed

**prefetch** allows loading the chunk in the background while showing on a different trigger (e.g., prefetch on idle, show on viewport).

**Functional resolver (modern):**
```ts
// user.resolver.ts
export const userResolver: ResolveFn<User> = (route, state) => {
  const userService = inject(UserService);
  const router = inject(Router);

  return userService.getUser(route.paramMap.get('id')!).pipe(
    catchError(() => {
      router.navigate(['/not-found']);
      return EMPTY; // prevents navigation if data load fails
    })
  );
};
```

**Route configuration:**
```ts
{
  path: 'user/:id/edit',
  component: UserEditComponent,
  resolve: { user: userResolver }
}
```

**Component access:**
```ts
export class UserEditComponent implements OnInit {
  user = inject(ActivatedRoute).snapshot.data['user'] as User;

  // Or reactive:
  user$ = inject(ActivatedRoute).data.pipe(map(d => d['user'] as User));
}
```

**Resolver vs component fetch:**
- **Resolver**: data guaranteed on init, no loading template needed, but navigation appears slow
- **Component fetch**: navigate instantly, show skeleton/spinner, better perceived performance

For most modern apps, fetching in the component with a skeleton UI provides better UX. Resolvers are appropriate for edit pages where displaying an empty form would be confusing.

```ts
@Component({
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  template: `
    <ul>
      @for (item of items; track item.id) {
        <li>{{ item.name }}</li>
      }
    </ul>
    <p>Total: {{ total }}</p>
  `
})
export class ItemListComponent {
  @Input() items: Item[] = []; // must pass NEW array reference

  get total() { return this.items.length; }
}
```

**This WORKS with OnPush (new reference):**
```ts
// Parent:
this.items = [...this.items, newItem]; // spread = new array
```

**This BREAKS OnPush (mutation):**
```ts
// Parent:
this.items.push(newItem); // same reference — OnPush component won't update!
```

**markForCheck() for WebSocket push:**
```ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class PriceService {
  constructor(private cd: ChangeDetectorRef) {
    webSocket('/prices').subscribe(price => {
      this.price = price;
      this.cd.markForCheck(); // tells Angular: this component subtree is dirty
    });
  }
}
```

**With signals (preferred modern approach):**
Signals automatically propagate changes without needing `markForCheck()`. An OnPush component with signal inputs updates fine because signals notify Angular's reactive graph directly.
